The contraceptive habits of Portuguese women reveal concerning trends, with a significant number of sexually active girls not using any form of birth control.
Despite receiving information on contraceptives at school, many young women still face risks.
In Peru, controversy surrounds the morning-after pill, with accusations of misinformation and debates over its classification.
The accessibility of emergency contraception is a contentious issue, with arguments for and against over-the-counter availability.
The debate extends to the US, where access to emergency contraceptives is a subject of protest and political scrutiny, highlighting the complex intersection of healthcare, ethics, and personal beliefs.
